Models for L are built from a nonempty set W that embodies the imaginative possibilities (“worlds”) available to an agent in the course of practical deliberation. Subsets of W are called propositions. Selection functions are defined as follows.
(2) Definition: A selection function s over W is a mapping from W × {A ⊆ W | A 6= ∅} to W such that for all w ∈ W and ∅ 6= A ⊆ W, s(w,A) ∈ A.
Thus, s(w,A) is a choice of world to represent A, where the choice depends on w. Next, each world is evaluated according to the model’s utility function.
(3) Definition: A utility function over W is a mapping from W to the real numbers.
Recall that S is the set of sentential variables in L. The last component of a model is an assignment of proposition to each variable in S.
(4) Definition: A truth-assignment over W is a mapping from S to the power set of W.
Models are defined as follows.
(5) Definition: A model is a quadruple (W, s, u, t) where
(a) W is a nonempty set of worlds;
(b) s is a selection function over W;
(c) u is a utility function over W;
(d) t is a truth-assignment over W;
